uction of CO2 by H2 on iron-sulfur phases gives formate/formic acid as a reduced C1 feedstock.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrothermal FeS/Fe3S4-mediated CO2 reduction to formate is consistent with iron-sulfur world chemistry and vent models summarized in the prompt and broadly aligned with hydrothermal carbon fixation concepts; included here as the hydrothermal feeder step connecting vent C1 chemistry to surface formaldehyde/formamide pathways. The specific role of reduced C1 species as prebiotic feedstock is consistent with W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user-style iron-sulfur chemistry and hydrothermal analyses cited in the report context; this connector is partially inferential but does not contradict the thymine literature.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface production and concentration of formaldehyde from formic acid/formate reservoirs\",\n      \"inputs\": [\n        \"mol_003\"\n      ],\n      \"outputs\": [\n        \"mol_004\"\n      ],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\n        \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\",\n        \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"\n      ],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-exposed evaporitic or geothermal setting; concentration by wet-dry cycling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical and thermal C1 interconversion in surface settings provides formaldehyde pools used for uracil hydroxymethylation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report identifies formaldehyde as a key prebiotic methylation feedstock produced abundantly by atmospheric photochemistry and also available in formamide-based systems. This step is a network-connecting concentration/availability step rather than a single canonical named experiment; it is included to show Hydrothermal -> Surface feed and is conservative relative to the literature emphasis on formaldehyde availability for uracil methylation (Robertson & Miller, 1995; Petera et al., 2021).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide accumulation from reduced C1-N chemistry in surface pools\",\n      \"inputs\": [\n        \"mol_003\"\n      ],\n      \"outputs\": [\n        \"mol_005\"\n      ],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\n        \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\",\n        \"montmorillonite\"\n      ],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic concentration; included as network connector to literature-supported formamide thermolysis chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Surface concentration and mineral-mediated stabilization generate formamide reservoirs that later undergo thermolysis.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formamide is the central one-pot precursor in the thymine literature and is treated as a key environmental feedstock in Saladino et al. (2003, 2012), Bhushan et al. (2016), Petera et al. (2021), Saladino et al. (2015), and Ferus et al. (2015). This explicit formation step is a necessary network connector and is marked as a bridging inference rather than a stand-alone thymine-forming experiment.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal/surface generation of acetate from reduced carbon chemistry\",\n      \"inputs\": [\n        \"mol_001\",\n        \"mol_002\"\n      ],\n      \"outputs\": [\n        \"mol_014\"\n      ],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\n        \"greigite (Fe3S4)\",\n        \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"\n      ],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite and magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent carbon-fixation analogue\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential CO2 reduction on iron-sulfur and oxide surfaces yields acetate/acetic acid as a reduced C2 feedstock.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The prompt specifically requires hydrothermal CO2 reduction to acetate on greigite/magnetite-like systems. Acetate is needed for the Schwartz-Chittenden wet-dry thymine route. This is a connector step consistent with iron-sulfur and Fischer-Tropsch-type vent chemistry summarized in the instructions.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanoacetylene hydrolysis to cyanoacetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\n        \"mol_008\"\n      ],\n      \"outputs\": [\n        \"mol_007\"\n      ],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\n        \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\",\n        \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"\n      ],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2/mineral surface concentration\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous shoreline or lagoon conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydration/hydrolysis of cyanoacetylene yields the more stable cyanoacetaldehyde, a key pyrimidine precursor.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cyanoacetylene is identified in the report as the primary C3 precursor and hydrolyzes in water to cyanoacetaldehyde, which is ~10^3 times more stable and highly productive in pyrimidine synthesis. This follows the framework discussed around Sanchez, Ferris, and Orgel (1966) and Robertson & Miller (1995). Mineral listing satisfies the surface-agent requirement; the chemistry itself is literature-grounded.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanoacetaldehyde plus urea gives cytosine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\n        \"mol_007\",\n        \"mol_006\"\n      ],\n      \"outputs\": [\n        \"mol_010\"\n      ],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\n        \"montmorillonite\",\n        \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"\n      ],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite-assisted concentration\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"drying lagoon / concentrated urea; high solute concentration\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Condensation of cyanoacetaldehyde with concentrated urea closes the pyrimidine ring to cytosine under drying conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Robertson and Miller reported 30-50% cytosine yield from cyanoacetaldehyde with concentrated urea in drying lagoon conditions at about 100C, making this one of the strongest literature-supported uracil-entry routes (Robertson & Miller, 1995).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolytic deamination of cytosine to uracil\",\n      \"inputs\": [\n        \"mol_010\"\n      ],\n      \"outputs\": [\n        \"mol_011\"\n      ],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\n        null\n      ],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"standing aqueous pool or geothermal cycling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cytosine undergoes hydrolytic deamination to uracil in water.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report explicitly treats cytosine hydrolysis as a major uracil source in prebiotic pyrimidine networks and uses it in discussing cyanoacetaldehyde/urea routes (Robertson & Miller, 1995; Shapiro, 1999 for cytosine deamination relevance).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Beta-alanine and urea condensation on clay to 5,6-dihydrouracil\",\n      \"inputs\": [\n        \"mol_009\",\n        \"mol_006\"\n      ],\n      \"outputs\": [\n        \"mol_012\"\n      ],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\n        \"montmorillonite\",\n        \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"\n      ],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"clay mineral surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporation/wet-dry cycling in pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Evaporation-driven condensation of beta-alanine and urea on clay forms dihydrouracil precursor under dehydrating conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This follows the Schwartz-Chittenden pathway in which beta-alanine and urea evaporated with clay minerals produce 5,6-dihydrouracil as a precursor to uracil/thymine (Chittenden & Schwartz, 1976; Schwartz & Chittenden, 1977).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"UV photodehydrogenation of 5,6-dihydrouracil to uracil\",\n      \"inputs\": [\n        \"mol_012\"\n      ],\n      \"outputs\": [\n        \"mol_011\"\n      ],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\n        \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\",\n        \"montmorillonite\"\n      ],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 photocatalysis\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-irradiated subaerial pool margin\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical dehydrogenation/aromatization of dihydrouracil restores the pyrimidine double bond system to uracil.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The beta-alanine route specifically requires UV photodehydrogenation of DHU to uracil in surface settings (Chittenden & Schwartz, 1976; Schwartz & Chittenden, 1977). TiO2 is included as a plausible terrestrial photocatalytic mineral while preserving the literature UV requirement.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanoacetylene plus cyanate gives cytosine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\n        \"mol_008\"\n      ],\n      \"outputs\": [\n        \"mol_010\"\n      ],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\n        \"montmorillonite\",\n        \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"\n      ],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral-assisted concentration\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"cyanate present in solution; 100C\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cyanoacetylene reacts with cyanate to form cytosine, which feeds uracil by hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ferris, Sanchez, and Orgel reported 19% cytosine formation from cyanoacetylene with cyanate at 100C, providing an alternative convergence route into the cytosine/uracil hub (Ferris, Sanchez, & Orgel, 1968). Cyanate is not separately tracked to keep the network compact; this compression is literature-based and topologically necessary.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide thermolysis on TiO2 gives uracil, 5-HMU, and thymine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\n        \"mol_005\"\n      ],\n      \"outputs\": [\n        \"mol_011\",\n        \"mol_013\",\n        \"mol_015\",\n        \"mol_004\",\n        \"mol_003\"\n      ],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\n        \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\",\n        \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"\n      ],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"433K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"neat formamide, 160C\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"TiO2-catalyzed thermolysis of neat formamide generates uracil and in situ formaldehyde/formic acid, enabling secondary hydroxymethylation to 5-HMU and minor thymine formation in one pot.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Saladino et al. showed that neat formamide heated at 160C with TiO2 produces thymine, 5-HMU, and related products, with TiO2 uniquely enabling thymine by promoting formamide decomposition to forma