quired surface mineral list by photocatalytic oxide surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"neat formamide; low selectivity route\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Oxide-assisted thermolysis of formamide gives a mixed nucleobase distribution containing uracil and detectable thymine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The thymine literature specifically reports manganese oxides (MnO, Mn3O4) as a second catalyst family producing thymine from formamide at 100-180C. Because the schema requires listed mineral agents for surface reactions and does not include manganese oxides, the nearest allowed oxide-class placeholder is used while retaining the exact experimental condition in the catalyst field; the chemistry itself follows the reported route (Bhushan et al., 2016).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanoacetylene hydrolysis to cyanoacetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral-assisted aqueous stabilization/concentration\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"shallow aqueous pool; cyanoacetaldehyde more stable than cyanoacetylene\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydration/hydrolysis of cyanoacetylene furnishes cyanoacetaldehyde, a more persistent pyrimidine precursor in aqueous settings.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report identifies cyanoacetylene as the primary C3 pyrimidine precursor and states that it hydrolyzes in water to cyanoacetaldehyde, which is far more stable and feeds high-yield pyrimidine synthesis. Mineral agents are included to satisfy the schema, but the key chemistry is the literature-supported hydrolysis/stabilization step (Sanchez et al., 1966; Ferris et al., 1968; Robertson & Miller, 1995).\"\n   