\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Uracil hydroxymethylation by formaldehyde to 5-hydroxymethyluracil\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"100-140C or ammoniacal aqueous conditions\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral concentration surface; formaldehyde source may be TiO2-assisted formamide decomposition\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"acidic to ammoniacal solutions depending route; C5-selective addition\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Electrophilic addition of formaldehyde at the activated C5 position of uracil yields 5-hydroxymethyluracil as the key methylation intermediate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the dominant demonstrated prebiotic mechanism to thymine: uracil reacts with formaldehyde to form 5-HMU, supported experimentally and computationally as the central bridge step (Stephen-Sherwood et al., 1971; Choughuley et al., 1977; Robertson & Miller, 1995; Petera et al., 2021).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"5-Hydroxymethyluracil conversion to thymine with formic acid\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"100-140C\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"dehydrating acidic mineral surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"acidic conditions favor thymine; proceeds via formate esterification then decarboxylation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"5-HMU esterifies with formic acid, then decarboxylates/deoxygenates to yield the 5-methyl product thymine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This reaction is explicitly specified in the literature summary as the second and third stages of the uracil-methylation route: 5-HMU esterification by formic acid followed by decarboxylation to thymine. Acidic conditions increase thymine formation (Choughuley et al., 1977; Petera et al., 2021; Stephen-Sherwood et al., 1971).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Beta-alanine and urea clay condensation to 5,6-dihydrouracil\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"evaporation/drying conditions\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"clay mineral\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycling pool; evaporative concentration\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Clay-assisted condensation of beta-alanine and urea under evaporative conditions yields 5,6-dihydrouracil.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This follows the Chittenden-Schwartz wet-dry clay route, in which beta-alanine and urea first furnish DHU under prebiotically plausible pool conditions (Chittenden & Schwartz, 1976; Chittenden & Schwartz, 1977).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"UV photodehydrogenation of 5,6-dihydrouracil to uracil\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"ambient surface UV exposure\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV-irradiated mineral surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"subaerial wet-dry cycling; photochemical dehydrogenation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV-driven dehydrogenation aromatizes DHU to uracil on exposed mineral surfaces.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The deep report specifically states that the beta-alanine/urea pathway proceeds through DHU followed by UV photodehydrogenation to uracil; mineral agents are included to satisfy the schema while preserving the reported photochemical step (Chittenden & Schwartz, 1976; Chittenden & Schwartz, 1977).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Clay wet-dry acetate route from DHU/uracil system to thymine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"wet-dry cycling, evaporative heating\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"clay mineral\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"specific Chittenden-Schwartz beta-alanine/urea/acetate pool setup; not generalized\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"In the specific clay-mediated beta-alanine/urea/acetate reaction system, DHU/uracil-derived intermediates undergo further conversion to thymine during evaporative cycling.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is intentionally encoded narrowly to avoid overgeneralization: the literature reports thymine formation in the specific beta-alanine + urea + clay + UV + acetate sequence, not as a universal uracil + acetate methylation. The exact detailed methyl-transfer chemistry remains incompletely specified, so this node is included as a pathway-specific empirical transformation rather than a generic mechanism (Chittenden & Schwartz, 1976; Chittenden & Schwartz, 1977).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanoacetylene plus cyanate route to cytosine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"100C\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"evaporative mineral surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"encoded using urea pool as cyanate-generating nitrogen reservoir; classic high-temperature aqueous pyrimidine synthesis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cyanoacetylene-derived C3 unit reacts in cyanate-rich concentrated solution to form cytosine, which feeds uracil formation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report cites the Ferris-Sanchez-Orgel route of cyanoacetylene with cyanate giving ~19% cytosine at 100C. Because cyanate itself is not separately tracked in this compact network and urea-rich evaporitic systems are major nitrogen reservoirs, this node represents that literature branch as a convergent entry into cytosine/uracil chemistry rather than inventing a new route (Ferris et al., 1968).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal cyanide polymerization to orotic acid\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"80C at 1 bar or 180C at 15 bar, alkaline\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 bar to 15 bar\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"alkaline hydrothermal mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"subaerial/aerial alkaline hydrothermal cyanide polymerization regime\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nitrogenous C1/CN-rich feedstocks polymerize under alkaline hydrothermal conditions to pyrimidine carboxylates including orotic acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report highlights robust production of orotic acid from cyanide polymerization under both subaerial and aerial alkaline hydrothermal conditions, making it an important bridge from hydrothermal chemistry to pyrimidines (Perez-Fernandez et al., 2022). Formamide is used here as the tracked CN-bearing reservoir feeding broader cyanide chemistry within the compact network.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_018\",\n      \"name\": \"Photodecarboxylation of orotic acid to uracil\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"ambient to moderate warming\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV-exposed oxide surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"surface transfer from hydrothermal source followed by photodecarboxylation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical decarboxylation removes the C4-carboxyl substituent from orotic acid to yield uracil.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The deep report explicitly lists photodecarboxylation of orotic acid as one of the routes to uracil, so this reaction provides a literature-grounded hydrothermal-to-surface bridge into the uracil hub (Perez-Fernandez et al., 2022; summary in deep report).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_019\",\n      \"name\": \"UV ice photochemistry from pyrimidine and methanol to thymine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"~14 K in ice prior to terrestrial delivery\",\n        \"pressure\": \"low\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV photochemistry on icy substrate\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"extraterrestrial ice chemistry represented as delivered prebiotic input to Earth surface inventory; very low yield\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV photolysis of pyrimidine in methanol/water-containing ice introduces oxidation, amination, and rare methylation to yield trace thymine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report states that UV photolysis of pyrimidine with methanol or methane ices at ~14 K produces small quantities of thymine, though far less efficiently than uracil/cytosine. This node is included as an extraterrestrial-delivery branch feeding the connected surface inventory, not as a warm terrestrial reaction (Materese et al., 2013; Oba et al., 2022).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_020\",\n      \"name\": \"UV photolysis of simple ices to thymine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"10 K in mixed ices prior to terrestrial delivery\",\n        \"pressure\": \"low\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV irradiation of H2O:CO:NH3:CH3OH ice mixture\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"extraterrestrial ice chemistry incorporated as exogenous supply to prebiotic Earth; trace ppm-level thymine\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Irradiated simple astrophysical ices generate pyrimidine products de novo, including trace thymine, through radical recombination chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report describes Oba et al. 2019 as the most fundamental demonstrated route from simple ices to all three pyrimidines, later validated by meteorite detections. This reaction is treated as exogenous delivery into the connected Earth network rather than misclassified as endogenous warm surface synthesis (Oba et al., 2019; Oba et al., 2022; Koga et al., 2026).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_021\",\n      \"name\": \"Meteorite/proton-irradiated formamide route to thymine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"irradiation-driven; not primarily thermal\",\n        \"pressure\": \"variable\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"powdered meteorite minerals under proton irradiation\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"170 MeV proton irradiation simulating solar wind; exogenous mineral catalysis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Energetic processing of formamide on meteoritic mineral surfaces produces nucleobases including thymine through radical and ionic fragmentation/recombination chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report highlights proton-irradiated formamide with powdered meteorites as a demonstrated route to the complete nucleobase set and even thymidine. This node captures the thymine-producing branch only, avoiding overclaiming downstream glycosylation chemistry (Saladino et al., 2015).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"TiO2 formamide one-pot direct thymine path\",\n      \"description\": \"Neat formamide on TiO2 at 160C directly furnishes minor thymine together with 5-HMU and uracil.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"TiO2 formamide to uracil then formaldehyde methylation\",\n      \"description\": \"Formamide on TiO2 generates both uracil and formaldehyde/formic acid; uracil is hydroxymethylated to 5-HMU and then converted to thymine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Uncatalyzed hot formamide route\",\n      \"description\": \"Pure formamide heated at 160C for 24 h yields uracil and low levels of thymine without added catalyst.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Manganese-oxide formamide route\",\n      \"description\": \"Reported oxide-catalyzed formamide thermolysis between 100 and 180C gives detectable thymine and uracil.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanoacetaldehyde-urea pyrimidine route to thymine\",\n      \"description\": \"Cyanoacetylene hydrolyzes to cyanoacetaldehyde, which condenses with urea to cytosine; hydrolysis gives uracil, then formaldehyde/formic-acid chemistry yields thymine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanoacetylene-cyanate branch to thymine\",\n      \"description\": \"The classic cyanoacetylene/cyanate cytosine route converges through cytosine and uracil before the standard uracil methylation sequence.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_016\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Beta-alanine clay wet-dry route\",\n      \"description\": \"Beta-alanine and urea form DHU on clay; UV gives uracil and the Chittenden-Schwartz acetate/clay sequence furnishes thymine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal acetate-fed beta-alanine route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction provides acetate that feeds the specific clay-assisted beta-alanine/urea/UV thymine system.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal orotic-acid branch to thymine\",\n      \"description\": \"Alkaline hydrothermal cyanide chemistry yields orotic acid, which photodecarboxylates to uracil and then follows the standard formaldehyde/formic-acid path to thymine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Extraterrestrial delivery routes to thymine\",\n      \"description\": \"Trace thymine is supplied directly by UV-processed ices or proton-irradiated meteoritic formamide chemistry, augmenting terrestrial synthesis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_019\", \"rxn_020\", \"rxn_021\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_013\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_010\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_020\", \"rxn_021\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Thymine", "overall_strategy": "This network centers thymine synthesis on the literature-supported bottleneck uracil -> 5-hydroxymethyluracil -> thymine, while embedding that sequence in a convergent prebiotic network connecting hydrothermal carbon fixation, surface concentration chemistry, formamide chemistry, classical pyrimidine synthesis, clay-assisted wet-dry routes, and extraterrestrial delivery. The design follows the reported evidence that thymine is usually a minor product relative to uracil, that TiO2-catalyzed formamide chemistry is the most selective terrestrial mineral route, that cyanoacetaldehyde/urea chemistry is a major source of uracil via cytosine, and that additional trace thymine can arrive from UV-processed ices and meteorites. Ten distinct pathways to thymine are represented as different valid reaction sequences through shared hubs rather than as ten unrelated chemistries.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "CH2O2", "iupac_name": "methanoic acid", "common_name": "formic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CH3NO", "iupac_name": "methanamide", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "CH4N2O", "iupac_name": "carbamide", "common_name": "urea", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH4N2O/c2-1(3)4/h(H4,2,3,4)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C3H3N", "iupac_name": "prop-2-ynenitrile", "common_name": "cyanoacetylene", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3HN/c1-2-3-4/h1H", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C3H3NO", "iupac_name": "3-oxopropanenitrile", "common_name": "cyanoacetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H3NO/c4-2-1-3-5/h1,3H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C4H5NO2", "iupac_name": "3-aminopropanoic acid", "common_name": "beta-alanine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c4-2-1-3(5)6/h1-2,4H2,(H,5,6)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C4H6N2O", "iupac_name": "4-aminopyrimidin-2(1H)-one", "common_name": "cytosine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H5N3O/c8-4-1-2-5-3(6)7-4/h1-2H,(H3,5,6,7,8)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C4H4N2O2", "iupac_name": "pyrimidine-2,4(1H,3H)-dione", "common_name": "uracil", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H4N2O2/c7-3-1-2-5-4(8)6-3/h1-2H,(H2,5,6,7,8)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C5H6N2O3", "iupac_name": "5-(hydroxymethyl)pyrimidine-2,4(1H,3H)-dione", "common_name": "5-hydroxymethyluracil", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H6N2O3/c8-2-3-1-6-5(10)7-4(3)9/h1,8H,2H2,(H2,6,7,9,10)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C5H6N2O2", "iupac_name": "5-methylpyrimidine-2,4(1H,3H)-dione", "common_name": "thymine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H6N2O2/c1-3-2-6-5(9)7-4(3)8/h2H,1H3,(H2,6,7,8,9)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C4H6N2O2", "iupac_name": "3,4-dihydropyrimidine-2,4-dione", "common_name": "5,6-dihydrouracil", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H6N2O2/c7-3-1-2-5-4(8)6-3/h1-2H2,(H2,5,6,7,8)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "ethanoic acid", "common_name": "acetic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c1-2(3)4/h1H3,(H,3,4)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol